The paper deals with scheduling algorithms, which is a topic in computer science that falls under several sub-categories. The use of "greedy-like" algorithms suggests that the paper may fall under the category of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The analysis of competitiveness and the consideration of smoothed competitiveness suggest that the paper may also fall under the categories of machine learning (cs.LG) and information theory (cs.IT). The use of game-theoretic concepts such as competitiveness and the analysis of worst-case scenarios suggest that the paper may also fall under the category of game theory (cs.GT). Finally, the consideration of online scheduling and the use of non-clairvoyant algorithms suggest that the paper may also fall under the category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI).
